description: From Middle English jorneman; from journe (from Old French jornee (“a day's work, a journey”)) and mon; equivalent to journey +‎ -man.

entries.meaning: A tradesman who has served an apprenticeship and is employed by a master tradesman.
A competent but undistinguished tradesman, especially one who works, and is paid by the day.
(sports) A player who plays on many different teams during the course of his career.
examples: The Los Angeles Lakers added journeyman forward Bob McAdoo to their roster in hopes that he could help them win a title.
